04429nam a22005415i 9780300157420DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20221993ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001574207 a10.12987/97803001574202doi  a(DE-B1597)625792  a(OCoLC)1322125698  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aGN494.5b.R67 1993eb 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a303.6/92221 aRoss, Marc, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Management of Conflict :bInterpretations and Interests in Comparative Perspective /cMarc Ross. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2022] 4c©1993  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. The Two Faces of Conflict -- t2. Interests, Interpretations, and the Culture of Conflict -- t3. The Culture of Constructive Conflict Management in Low-Conflict Societies -- t4. The Conflict Management Process: Changing Interests and Interpretations -- t5. The Sources of Conflict and Strategies of Conflict Management -- t6. Successful Conflict Management -- t7. Failed Conflict Management -- t8. Psychocultural Prerequisites for Constructive Conflict Management -- t9. Toward More Constructive Conflict Management -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aComplex social and political conflicts invariably have multiple roots rather than a single clear cause, and they are therefore difficult to manage effectively. Conflicts are about the interpretations of opponents' motives as well as the interests that antagonists pursue. Conflict management is most effective when it addresses not only the specific objects of contention but also adversaries' deeper, emotion-laden fears.Drawing on research and ideas delineated in his companion book, The Culture of Conflict, Marc Howard Ross offers a cross-cultural approach to conflict management. He identifies key features of constructive conflict management societies and evaluates three strategies of conflict management—self help, joint problem-solving, and third-party decision making—showing how each succeeds or fails in dealing with both disputants' interests and interpretations as causes of conflict. Exploring a wide variety of conflict management successes and failures—including the confrontation between MOVE and the city of Philadelphia, a public housing dispute in New York City, the return to warfare in post-colonial highland New Guinea, persistent hostility in Northern Ireland, and the Camp David Accords—Ross explains that how disputants' interests and interpretations are addressed affects the course of each dispute, its intensity, and the degree to which the dispute results in a constructive outcome. He offers the hypothesis that in bitter disputes modifying opponents' interpretations is a prerequisite for bridging differences in interests, stresses the need for models of successful conflict management, and suggests ways to expand constructive conflict management.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aConflict (Psychology)vCross-cultural studies. 0aConflict managementvCross-cultural studies. 0aEthnopsychology. 0aPolitical anthropology. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z978311053801440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030015742040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300157420423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300157420/original  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles